Path

Path and PathFollow constrain the movement of child nodes

Path lets you design a smooth curve with Bezier interpolation in 3D space. The PathFollow node moves along a parent Path and makes its children follow the path.

You can either draw the path in the viewport or generate curves at runtime. In turn, the two nodes are great for path-following mechanics.

For example, using Path and PathFollow, you could use the AStar pathfinding algorithm to construct paths for units to follow at runtime in a grid-based game.

The Path node can work on its own without the PathFollow child. Well cover this when generating a laser beam that shoots from off-screen to a target.

On the other hand, PathFollow only works as a child of Path, where it gets constrained on the parents curve.

In this guide, youll learn to:

  • Set up the Path and PathFollow combo for making nodes follow a designated path.
  • Make a player unit move along a path generated using an AStar algorithm in real-time.
  • Generate a random path for a card game for an effective animation.
  • Move a platform on a predefined path in a side-scroll demo.
  • Create a sweeping laser animation coming from outside the screen.
  • Use the Path and PathFollow in a non-standard way to create a directed force field that influences RigidBody nodes.
  • Grind rails with obstacles randomly placed along the path.

Setting up a Path and PathFollow to move along the path

While you can use the Path node on its own to generate Bezier curves, the most common way to use it is to sample positions along the path.

To follow a Path nodes curve, you must add a PathFollow node as a child of it, like so:

You need to add a new Curve3D to the Paths Curve property to draw a path.

You can then draw the path in the 3D viewport using the toolbar that appears at the top:

Then you can manipulate the location of PathFollow along the curve using either its Offset or Unit Offset in the Inspector:

Updating either property automatically updates the other.

Paths key features

The purpose of the Path node is to hold the Curve3D resource. This is its key property.

The Curve3D resource

You can either draw the curve in the 3D viewport in the editor or manipulate it in code. Both ways are helpful depending on the case.

The node precalculates points along the curve using the Bake Interval property to save on performance. This value represents the distance in 3D units between two of those points.

By default, the Curve3D resource uses a Bake Interval of 0.2, meaning itll precalculate one point every 0.2 units.

As well see, this property, combined with PathFollows Cubic Interp property, can generate smooth paths, even if we have a Curve with sharp corners.

Heres a preview with Bake Interval set to 2 and Cubic Interp both on and off:

Note: If the Bake Interval is too large, the arcs followed by PathFollow can end up very different from the smooth curve you drew.

Curve3D has one more property, Up Vector -> Enabled:

When turned on, Godot precalculates up vectors (the local Y direction) on top of precalculating points along the path. At the time of writing, the tilt of up vectors is challenging to manipulate.

The Up Vector -> Enabled property only has effect when setting the PathFollow nodes Rotation Mode to Oriented. This setting causes the node following the path to orient towards the local up vector.

Note: At this time, Orient is the only mode that works alongside None. The other modes dont work in Godot 3.3 but this is a known problem, and the Godot developers are working on solutions.

PathFollows key features

PathFollow only works as a child of a Path node. Its key features are that it moves and rotates along its parent path.

Offset-based position and rotation

You control the nodes position along the parent path using either the Offset or the Unit Offset property.

Changing either property causes the other to update as well. The main difference is that the Offset is in units while the Unit Offset is in the [0, 1] range.

A Unit Offset of 0 corresponds to the start of the path and 1 corresponds to the end. This makes Unit Offset especially useful for interpolating from the start to the end in a set time without having to calculate the step size yourself.

Smooth paths with cubic interpolation

As we saw, the actual path PathFollow takes depends on the Curve3Ds Bake Interval property. The larger the Bake Interval, the more jagged and imprecise the path becomes.

When you turn on Cubic Interp on the PathFollow, it smoothly interpolates between the cached curve points, even if the curve has sharp corners.

Optional rotation along the curve

The other notable feature of PathFollow is the Rotation Mode property. If we set it to Oriented, the node aligns its rotation to match the curve direction.

This works by aligning the local Z-axis along the paths tangent and the Y-axis along the up vector. For this to work, we have to turn on Up Vector -> Enabled on Curve3D.

To turn off this behavior, we can choose None for Rotation Mode.

As mentioned before, at the time of writing, the other rotation options have unexpected behavior.

Horizontal and vertical offsets

As the name implies, H Offset and V Offset add horizontal and vertical offsets to the position of the PathFollow node.

For example, by duplicating a PathFollow twice:

And setting different H Offset and V Offset on each, we can get a uniform mob movement pattern:

Although this setup looks very mechanical, adding some randomness to the H Offset and V Offset properties can give interesting results.

Looping and cyclic curves

Finally, the Loop property forces any Offset value outside the Curve3D length to wrap around. This is useful for cyclic paths. We create a cyclic path by having the first and last points coincide.

Theres no need to place the last point of the curve manually. We can generate a final point that aligns perfectly with the first using the Close Curve button from the toolbar:

How to use Path and PathFollow in practice

This section looks at standard examples of using the Path and PathFollow combo and more creative cases.

Real-time paths with the AStar algorithm

In this example, we have a game that uses a GridMap and the AStar algorithm to construct a path for the player ship to follow.

We use the Path and PathFollow combo to create real-time paths on player mouse click. The path starts at the current ship position and ends at the center of the clicked tile.

To find and follow paths, we use the following nodes:

  • A GridMap serves as the games grid. We treat occupied cells as obstacles.
  • A Path with a child PathFollow to generate a curve and follow it.
    • We add a character as a child of the PathFollow, a MeshInstance, thatll automatically move along with its parent.

The additional nodes are:

  • A Camera node is required for 3D scenes to work and get the mouse interaction with the 3D game world.
  • A MeshInstance called HaloMesh that acts as the mouse pointer to know where we click on.
  • A MeshInstance called Ground which is just a plane that acts as the ground floor.
  • A DirectionalLight to make the scene more appealing.

We make sure to set Rotation Mode to Oriented and turn off the PathFollows Loop property. Otherwise, the ship restarts the path movement from the beginning forever.

Note: Rotation Mode forces the Z direction of the child nodes to face the path tangent.

Before coding the pathfinding demo, we take a short detour to add a missing function to GridMap.

Unlike the Tilemap node, the GridMap node doesnt have a built-in method to get the size of the volume occupied by the used cells. But this is a function we can code ourselves. In a GridMap.gd script attached to GridMap, we add this code:

extends GridMap


func get_used_aabb() -> AABB:
    var cells := get_used_cells()
    cells.sort()

    var first: Vector3 = cells.front()
    var last: Vector3 = cells.back()
    return AABB(first, last - first + Vector3.ONE)

The AABB object is the 3D equivalent of Rect2 used in 2D games. Its an upright box representing an objects bounds in the game world. In our case, the AABB represents the volume in number of used cells.

Getting back on track to coding the pathfinding demo, we start by referencing our necessary nodes from code:

# We reference our scene's key nodes and use them for pathfinding.
onready var _camera: Camera = $Camera
onready var _gridmap: GridMap = $GridMap
onready var _halo_mesh: MeshInstance = $HaloMesh
onready var _path: Path = $Path
onready var _path_follow: PathFollow = $Path/PathFollow

Moving the PathFollow node along the Paths Curve3D happens in _process().

By default, we disable _process() and only enable it when updating the curve, after a mouse click from the player.

We need a few variables to calculate the player ship speed:

## The ship's maximum speed in units per second.
const SPEED_MAX := 16.0

## The ship's current speed in units per second.
var _speed := 0.0
var _acceleration := 6.0

As our environment has different heights, we need to keep track of the GridMap level the mouse points to on the Y-axis.

var _level := 0 setget _set_level

func _set_level(value: int) -> void:
    # We use `posmod()` to make sure that value never exits the `[0,
    # _gridmap_aabb.size.y]` range.
    _level = posmod(value, _gridmap_aabb.size.y)

With that out of the way, we move to the _process() function:

func _process(delta: float) -> void:
    _speed = min(_speed + _acceleration * delta, SPEED_MAX)
    _path_follow.offset += _speed * delta

    if _path_follow.offset >= _path.curve.get_baked_length():
        _speed = 0.0
        set_process(false)

To construct the curve based on the AStar algorithm and issue the move command, we:

  1. Find the path to the grid cell the player clicked.
  2. Clear the current Path Curve and add the points from the first step to it.
  3. Enable _process() to start the ship movement.

To get the ship to move along the path, we call two functions: find_path() and move_along().

func _unhandled_input(event: InputEvent) -> void:
    if event.is_action_pressed("click"):
        move_along(find_path())
    elif event.is_action_pressed("level_up"):
        _set_level(_level + 1)
    elif event.is_action_pressed("level_down"):
        _set_level(_level - 1)

    # On mouse motion we recalculate the `HaloMesh` position based on the mouse
    # pointer.
    if event is InputEventMouseMotion:
        # We convert to map coordinates and reconvert to world coordinates in
        # order to round the `position` to the nearest `GridMap` cell.
        var position := _gridmap.world_to_map(mouse_position_to_xyz(event.position))
        _halo_mesh.translation = _gridmap.map_to_world(position.x, position.y, position.z)
        _halo_mesh.translation += _gridmap_offset

## Returns the location in 3D space based on a ray shooting from the mouse
## position and intersecting a plane that is perpendicular with `Vecctor3.UP`.
## Its depth is given by `_level`.
func mouse_position_to_xyz(mouse_position: Vector2) -> Vector3:
    # We use a small "uncertainty" to the `_level` so we won't worry about
    # rounding errors.
    return Plane(Vector3.UP, _gridmap.cell_size.y * _level + 1e-4).intersects_ray(
        _camera.project_ray_origin(mouse_position),
        _camera.project_ray_normal(mouse_position)
    )

The find_path() function asks the AStar object for a path, an array of grid coordinates to move to the target position.

## Gets the `AStar` point-path given by the `PathFollow` current position and
## the input `HaloMesh` position which correspond to the mouse pointer.
func find_path() -> PoolVector3Array:
    var out: PoolVector3Array = []

    # First get the start and finish `AStar` indices based on `PathFollow` and
    # respectively the mouse click locations, through `HaloMesh`.
    var start_index := xyz_to_index(_gridmap.world_to_map(_path_follow.translation))
    var finish_point := _gridmap.world_to_map(_halo_mesh.translation)
    var finish_index := xyz_to_index(finish_point)

    # We also check `_gridmap_aabb.has_point()` because `xyz_to_index` works
    # only for positive positions
    if (_gridmap_aabb.has_point(finish_point)
        and _astar.has_point(start_index)
        and _astar.has_point(finish_index)
    ):
        out = _astar.get_point_path(start_index, finish_index)

    return out

We define two utility functions to convert 3D coordinates to unique indices and vice-versa. We need this as the pathfinding algorithm works with indices.

# We use the following two functions to convert values between grid coordinates
# and indices.
func xyz_to_index(offset: Vector3) -> int:
    return int(offset.x + _gridmap_aabb.size.x * (offset.y + _gridmap_aabb.size.y * offset.z))


func index_to_xyz(index: int) -> Vector3:
    var x := index % int(_gridmap_aabb.size.x)
    var y := (index / int(_gridmap_aabb.size.x)) % int(_gridmap_aabb.size.y)
    var z := index / int(_gridmap_aabb.size.x * _gridmap_aabb.size.y)
    return Vector3(x, y, z)

Last is the move_along() function, which takes the path output by find_path() and updates the Path nodes curve for the ship to move to the target.

## Generates a new curve based on a path output by the AStar object and turns on
## processing.
func move_along(path: Array) -> void:
    if path.empty():
        return

    _path.curve.clear_points()
    _path.curve.add_point(_path_follow.translation)

    for index in range(1, path.size()):
        var point := _gridmap.map_to_world(path[index].x, path[index].y, path[index].z)
        point += _gridmap_offset
        _path.curve.add_point(point)

    _path_follow.offset = 0.0
    set_process(true)

Random paths for card games

In this demo, we animate cards moving from the players hand to the table slots.

To do so, we generate random motion paths.

This example uses this scene setup:

  • The Slots are locations to which the cards can move.
  • Each card lives in the Hand and is composed of:
    • A Path with a child PathFollow.
    • As a child of the PathFollow, we have the cards visuals.
    • We use a Tween node to animate the PathFollows offset and move the card along the path.

Along with the nodes that contribute specifically to the mechanics, we have a Camera since were dealing with 3D.

The DirectionalLight improves the screens looks, and the Table node is a MeshInstance holding a plane mesh acting as the visual representation of the table.

To learn more about designing a card, check out the PanelContainer guide.

To animate the cards, we calculate a path with three points, where the first and last are:

  1. The first point is the cards position.
  2. The last point is the position of the first empty slot from the left.

To add variety to the animation, we construct the curves middle point by first calculating the average position between the first and last point.

Then we add a random perturbation on the X-axis.

Given an array of target positions, a RandomNumberGenerator, and references to the relevant nodes, we can construct a curve when the player clicks on a card.

We attach the following code to each card.

## Stores the position of every slot the card can move to.
## See `setup()` below for its initialization.
var _slot_positions := []
var _rng := RandomNumberGenerator.new()

onready var _path_follow: PathFollow = $PathFollow
onready var _card: MeshInstance = $PathFollow/BoardCard
# Each card has a visual border we use to detect when the player hovers and
# clicks the card. You can do that the Area node.
onready var _card_area: Area = $PathFollow/BoardCard/Area
onready var _tween: Tween = $Tween

func setup(slot_positions: Array) -> void:
    _slot_positions = slot_positions

We handle this interaction in the _on_CardArea_input_event() function. We first connect to the Area nodes signals in _ready():

func _ready() -> void:
    _card_area.connect("input_event", self, "_on_CardArea_input_event")
    _card_area.connect("mouse_entered", self, "_on_CardArea_mouse_entered_exited", [true])
    _card_area.connect("mouse_exited", self, "_on_CardArea_mouse_entered_exited", [false])
    _rng.randomize()

And for the actual path construction:

# The `Area` `input_event` signal emits when the player applies input to the node,
# for example, by clicking on it. It won't trigger if the player clicks elsewhere
# on the screen.
func _on_CardArea_input_event(
        _camera: Node,
        event: InputEvent,
        _click_position: Vector3,
        _click_normal: Vector3,
        _shape_idx: int
    ) -> void:
    if event.is_action_pressed("click"):
        # Get the next slot position, this will also shrink the array.
        var slot_position: Vector3 = _slot_positions.pop_back()

        # Find the mean position between the card and the slot and apply
        # a random offset on the X axis for added variation.
        var offset: Vector3 = (_path_follow.translation + slot_position) / 2.0
        offset.x += _rng.randf_range(-1, 1)

        # Add the points to the curve: the current card position, the middle offset and
        # the final slot position.
        curve.clear_points()
        curve.add_point(_path_follow.translation)
        curve.add_point(offset)
        curve.add_point(slot_position)

        # Here, we animate the card moving along the path.
        _tween.stop_all()
        _tween.interpolate_property(
            _path_follow, "unit_offset", 0, 1, 0.6, Tween.TRANS_QUAD, Tween.EASE_OUT
        )

        # We also animate the rotation with the `Tween` node because we want a specific orientation
        # to match the table. For that reason we have `PathFollow.rotation_mod = ROTATION_NONE`.
        _tween.interpolate_property(
            _path_follow, "rotation:x", _path_follow.rotation.x,
            -PI / 2.0, 0.6, Tween.TRANS_QUAD, Tween.EASE_OUT
        )
        _tween.interpolate_property(
            _path_follow, "rotation:y", _path_follow.rotation.y,
            _rng.randf_range( -PI, PI) / 20.0, 0.6, Tween.TRANS_QUAD, Tween.EASE_OUT
        )

        # We animate the card going up when hovering it with the mouse. So we
        # need to move it back to its original position quickly to avoid having
        # it offset from the card slot.
        _tween.interpolate_property(_card, "translation:y", _card.translation.y, 0, 0.1, Tween.TRANS_CUBIC, Tween.EASE_IN, 0.7)
        _tween.start()

        # Once the player placed a card, they shouldn't be able to click it
        # anymore. That's why we disconnect from the signals.
        _card_area.disconnect("input_event", self, "_on_CardArea_input_event")
        _card_area.disconnect("mouse_entered", self, "_on_CardArea_mouse_entered_exited")
        _card_area.disconnect("mouse_exited", self, "_on_CardArea_mouse_entered_exited")

Side-scroller platforms following a complex path

In this example, we construct a platform following an arbitrary curve instead of the regular horizontal or vertical motions.

Interestingly enough, this demo doesnt need any code other than the code for camera and player movement, and perhaps interactables, like the chest.

To make the Platform do a complete cycle, we animate the PathFollows unit_offset property from 0 to 1:

I picked an 8 second long animation for the cycle, made sure to autoplay the Move animation, and made it loop.

In Godot 3.3, we cant make the Player ( KinematicBody) stick to the Platform during its animation by making the Platform a KinematicBody as well.

In this demo, the Platform node under PathFollow is a KinematicBody with a simple cube MeshInstance and CollisionShape.

We also need to set the AnimationPlayer -> Process Mode to Physics to synchronize it with the physics frames. Godot 3.4 is looking to improve the situation there with new code to synchronize KinematicBody nodes and animated objects.

Paths as force fields

Thinking outside the box, we can use the Path and PathFollow combo for other purposes, apart from constraining nodes movement on curves.

In this demo, we use paths to construct a force field that directs the movement of RigidBody nodes:

To start us off, we have this scene setup:

The Field node contains two paths we use to apply a force to nearby asteroids. The asteroids live under a separate node, Asteroids.

On the Path nodes, we defined a few export variables for easy access in the Inspector:

The idea is that the force is strongest if an asteroid is right on the path, with a value of Force Size.

It then decays up to Decay Distance following the Decay Curve profile.

export var force_size := 500.0
export var decay_curve: Curve = Curve.new()
export var decay_distance := 500.0

On the root node, we have a script for calculating the force based on the paths and applying it to the RigidBody nodes under Asteroids.

Start by getting references to the appropriate nodes:

onready var _field: Spatial = $Field
onready var _asteroids: Spatial = $Asteroids

We can calculate the force at a given point anyway we want, based on the path. This is how we do it here:

## Calculate a force at the given input position, based on the proximity to the
## available paths.
func calculate_force(input_position: Vector3) -> Vector3:
    var force := Vector3.ZERO

    for path in _field.get_children():
        var path_follow: PathFollow = path.get_node("PathFollow")

        # Move `PathFollow` to the closest point to `input_position`, on the curve.
        path_follow.offset = path.curve.get_closest_offset(input_position)

        # Calculate the force at distance given the decay `Curve`.
        var vector_from_input_position := path_follow.translation - input_position
        var force_size_at_distance = path.force_size * path.decay_curve.interpolate_baked(
            min(vector_from_input_position.length() / path.decay_distance, 1.0)
        )
        force += force_size_at_distance * path_follow.transform.basis.z

    return force

We calculate the total force by adding the contribution to all paths under the Field node.

Then for every RigidBody, in our case called PushedAsteroid, we apply the force:

func _physics_process(_delta: float) -> void:
    for asteroid in _asteroids.get_children():
        asteroid.add_central_force(calculate_force(asteroid.translation))

Laser swiping effect

Well see how to fire a laser from off-screen onto a moving target for this demonstration.

The setup for this scene is as follows:

The CraftRacer moves in an infinite loop along the PathShip curve.

The laser firing mechanism works like this:

  1. We pick a random position off-screen on a hemisphere, so the laser always appears to shoot from the top.
  2. We pick two random positions on a hemisphere that faces the camera at a radius that matches the Shield visual. These positions are relative to CraftRacer.
  3. We swipe the PathLaser using the Tween node and the two random positions from the previous point.

We fire the laser every time Timer emits the timeout signal.

We use a CSGPolygon called Laser with a translucent material for the laser visual.

We make sure to turn on Invert Faces, otherwise, the laser shape looks wrong.

We start coding by storing the desired laser swipe duration in a constant and a RandomNumberGenerator to randomize the laser.

We also store references to all the nodes we need in the script.

## The duration of the laser beam's swipe animation in seconds.
const LASER_ANIMATION_DURATION := 0.4

# We use a random number generator to randomize the swipe animation, as well as
# the position of the laser outside the screen.
var _rng := RandomNumberGenerator.new()

onready var _path_follow: PathFollow = $PathShip/PathFollow
onready var _path_laser_curve: Curve3D = $PathLaser.curve
onready var _timer: Timer = $Timer
onready var _tween: Tween = $Tween

As I said, we fire the laser every time the Timer emits the timeout signal.

We also need to reset the Laser points at the end of each swipe. So we prepare the connections and defaults in the _ready() function and the cleanup in _on_Tween_tween_all_completed():

func _ready() -> void:
    _rng.randomize()
    _timer.connect("timeout", self, "_on_Timer_timeout")
    _tween.connect("tween_all_completed", self, "_on_Tween_tween_all_completed")


func _on_Tween_tween_all_completed() -> void:
    _path_laser_curve.clear_points()

Next, we have the _on_Timer_timout() and the _animate_laser_swipe() functions:

func _on_Timer_timeout() -> void:
    var offset := _randv_hemisphere(50)
    for _i in range(2):
        _path_laser_curve.add_point(offset)


    _tween.stop_all()
    _tween.interpolate_method(
        self, "_animate_laser_swipe", _randv_hemisphere(1), _randv_hemisphere(1),
        LASER_ANIMATION_DURATION, Tween.TRANS_LINEAR, Tween.EASE_IN
    )
    _tween.start()
    # Seeking forces the tween to update the animation state. Otherwise, the laser's position won't
    # update until the next frame, causing visual artifacts.
    _tween.seek(0.0)

    _timer.wait_time = _rng.randf_range(1, 2)


func _animate_laser_swipe(offset: Vector3) -> void:
    var position := _path_follow.translation + offset
    _path_laser_curve.set_point_position(1, position)

We finish with _randv_hemisphere() for generating random numbers on a hemisphere of a given radius.

func _randv_hemisphere(radius: int) -> Vector3:
    var v := Vector3.RIGHT.rotated(Vector3.DOWN, _rng.randf_range(0.0, PI))
    return radius * v.rotated(v.cross(Vector3.UP), _rng.randf_range(0.0, 0.5 * PI))

Rail grinding

In this demo, we look at a rail grinding mechanic where the player jumps over obstacles.

At first glance, the scene setup seems more complicated, but if we focus on the Path node and its children, there isnt much we havent already seen here.

The novelty is that we place the Camera node under PlayerGroup to keep it attached to the player as it moves on the curve.

We keep it independent of the player because we want to jump up and down without having the camera follow this movement.

The CSGPolygon is used to construct the players path, which makes the demo feel grounded.

For this setup, instead of using math for the jump mechanic, well use the Tween node for the same effect.

We use blue noise to generate non-overlapping random positions to place obstacles along the paths.

The obstacle scene is made out of an Area root node with a MeshInstance and a CollisionShape to detect collisions:

We use a cube for its collision shape:

We expose the MeshInstance in code so we wont call get_node("MeshInstance") all the time in the demo:

onready var mesh_instance: MeshInstance = $MeshInstance

We start with declaring the obstacle scene, a few useful constants, and node references:

const Obstacle := preload("Obstacle.tscn")

# We change the obstacle color when the player touches it for visual feedback.
const COLORS := {"default": Color("4da6ff"), "touch": Color("eb564b")}
# We generate a number of obstacles between `[OBSTACLES.min, OBSTACLES.max]` per path.
const OBSTACLES := {"min": 5, "max": 11}
const JUMP := {"height": 1, "time": 0.3}
const SPEED := 8

var _rng := RandomNumberGenerator.new()

onready var _path_follow: PathFollow = $Path/PathFollow
onready var _player_group: Spatial = $Path/PathFollow/PlayerGroup
onready var _player: Area = $Path/PathFollow/PlayerGroup/Player
onready var _tween: Tween = $Tween
onready var _obstacles: Spatial = $Obstacles

Next, we generate obstacles on the path in _ready():

func _ready() -> void:
    _rng.randomize()
    _player.connect("area_entered", self, "_on_Player_area_entered_exited", [true])
    _player.connect("area_exited", self, "_on_Player_area_entered_exited", [false])

    # Generate obstacles on paths.
    for r in _rng_blue_noise(_rng.randi_range(OBSTACLES.min, OBSTACLES.max)):
        _path_follow.unit_offset = r
        var obstacle: Area = Obstacle.instance()
        obstacle.transform = _path_follow.transform
        _obstacles.add_child(obstacle)

    # After placing the obstacles, reset the `PathFollow` offset position.
    _path_follow.unit_offset = 0.0

Heres the blue noise function we use to generate random positions along the path:

## Returns an array of the given size with random numbers between `(0, 1)` that have at least
## `padding` distance between them.
func _rng_blue_noise(size: int, padding: float = 0.01) -> Array:
    var out := []
    var cell := 1.0 / size
    for i in range(size):
        var x := padding + cell * i
        out.push_back(_rng.randf_range(x, x + cell - padding))
    return out

When the player touches the obstacles, we change their color for visual feedback:

func _on_Player_area_entered_exited(area: Area, has_entered: bool) -> void:
    var material: Material = area.mesh_instance.get_active_material(0)
    if has_entered:
        material.albedo_color = COLORS.touch
    else:
        material.albedo_color = COLORS.default

We finish with the player controls and movement:

func _input(event: InputEvent) -> void:
    if not _tween.is_active() and event.is_action_pressed("jump_3d"):
        _tween.interpolate_property(
            _player, "translation:y", 0, JUMP.height, JUMP.time,Tween.TRANS_QUAD, Tween.EASE_OUT
        )
        _tween.interpolate_property(
            _player, "translation:y", JUMP.height, 0, JUMP.time, Tween.TRANS_QUAD, Tween.EASE_IN,
            JUMP.time
        )
        _tween.start()


func _physics_process(delta: float) -> void:
    _path_follow.offset += SPEED * delta
    if _path_follow.unit_offset >= 1.0:
        set_physics_process(false)

Note: We use the Tween node for the jump animation instead of calculating the trajectory ourselves.

This is possible because jumping under acceleration describes a parabola, and this is what we get when using the TRANS_QUAD transition type.
